      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Hard Life of Actors</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Mike Baker, president emeritus of Aftra, mocks Leslie Saint Bornstein (Sept 29 Op-Ed) for crossing actors' picket lines</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Strike No One Can Win,'' by Leslie Saint Bornstein (Op-Ed, Sept. 29):</p>
        <p>No one ever wins a strike. We just aren't going to lose this one.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Strike No One Can Win,'' by Leslie Saint Bornstein (Op-Ed, Sept. 29):</p>
        <p>No one ever wins a strike. We just aren't going to lose this one.</p>
        <p>Ms. Bornstein doesn't know how to take her chances without unfairly climbing over the truly dedicated. Yes, she is a scab.</p>
        <p>Why can't she make it in the same manner that 135,000 Screen Actors Guild members and 63,000 Aftra members managed to get their union membership cards? They did it the right way. They worked hard to become professionals in one of the toughest occupations in the world.</p>
        <p>MIKE BAKER  New York, Sept. 29, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is president emeritus of the New York branch of Aftra.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
